    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    20,79
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        19,86
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 37.2 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 55.7% of the total average of 66.8   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 20.8 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 19.9 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,92
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,05
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 20.2 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.92 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.05 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    21,07
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        20,06
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 25.0 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 64.6% of the total average of 38.7   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 21.1 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 20.1 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,91
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 16.4 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.91 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    20,49
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        19,48
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 16.4 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 52.4% of the total average of 31.2   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 20.5 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 19.5 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,98
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 15.5 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.98 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    20,18
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        18,85
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 15.2 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 49.6% of the total average of 30.6   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 20.2 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 18.8 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,20
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,80
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,92
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 16.1 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.92 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    20,74
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        19,85
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 16.2 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 52.5% of the total average of 30.9   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 20.7 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 19.8 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,02
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,98
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,11
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,06
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 16.6 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.11 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.06 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          35,02
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          36,75
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          35,02
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          12,07
    Stall Dispatch Stall                                                              inst                           0,02
    Stall Drain                                                                       inst                           0,01
    Stall IMC Miss                                                                    inst                           3,19
    Stall LG Throttle                                                                 inst                              0
    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                          11,41
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,02
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                              0
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,01
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,43
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,07
    Selected                                                                          inst                              1
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           0,95
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,58
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    24,52
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        21,90
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 12.1 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 34.5% of the total average of 35.0 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 11.4 cycles being stalled waiting for a scoreboard dependency on a 
          L1TEX (local, global, surface, texture) operation. This represents about 32.6% of the total average of 35.0   
          cycles between issuing two instructions. To reduce the number of cycles waiting on L1TEX data accesses        
          verify the memory access patterns are optimal for the target architecture, attempt to increase cache hit      
          rates by increasing data locality or by changing the cache configuration, and consider moving frequently      
          used data to shared memory.                                                                                   
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 24.5 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 21.9 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           5,72
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          94,28
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,76
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,06
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 17.5 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.76 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.06 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          30,77
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          32,77
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          30,77
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          11,59
    Stall Dispatch Stall                                                              inst                           0,01
    Stall Drain                                                                       inst                           0,01
    Stall IMC Miss                                                                    inst                           4,29
    Stall LG Throttle                                                                 inst                              0
    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                           9,15
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,01
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                              0
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,02
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,50
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,06
    Selected                                                                          inst                              1
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           1,03
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,49
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    25,29
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        21,66
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 11.6 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 37.7% of the total average of 30.8 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 25.3 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 21.7 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

          multiprocessors. This can underutilize some multiprocessors. If you do not intend to execute this kernel      
          concurrently with other workloads, consider reducing the block size to have at least one block per            
          multiprocessor or increase the size of the grid to fully utilize the available hardware resources.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           5,82
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          94,18
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,90
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,06
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 17.2 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.90 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.06 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          32,60
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          34,95
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          32,60
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          12,46
    Stall Dispatch Stall                                                              inst                           0,01
    Stall Drain                                                                       inst                           0,02
    Stall IMC Miss                                                                    inst                           4,86
    Stall LG Throttle                                                                 inst                              0
    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                           7,45
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,01
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                              0
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                           0,00
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,02
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,56
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,08
    Selected                                                                          inst                              1
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           1,10
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,57
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    27,66
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        23,24
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 12.5 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 38.2% of the total average of 32.6 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 27.7 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 23.2 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   The grid for this launch is configured to execute only 1 blocks, which is less than the GPU's 14              
          multiprocessors. This can underutilize some multiprocessors. If you do not intend to execute this kernel      
          concurrently with other workloads, consider reducing the block size to have at least one block per            
          multiprocessor or increase the size of the grid to fully utilize the available hardware resources.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,08
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,92
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,88
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 16.4 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.88 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          30,90

    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,58
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    28,86
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        24,25
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 13.0 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 42.0% of the total average of 30.9 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.

    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1

    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           3,08
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 16.2 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          3.08 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,33
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,67
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,89
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 15.8 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.89 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          29,91
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          32,10
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          29,91
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          12,27
    Stall Dispatch Stall                                                              inst                           0,01
    Stall Drain                                                                       inst                           0,02
    Stall IMC Miss                                                                    inst                           6,16
    Stall LG Throttle                                                                 inst                              0
    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                           6,38
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,02
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                              0
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                           0,00
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,02
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,58
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,09
    Selected                                                                          inst                              1
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           1,10
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,58
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    28,61
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        23,89
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 12.3 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 41.0% of the total average of 29.9 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 28.6 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 23.9 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

          multiprocessors. This can underutilize some multiprocessors. If you do not intend to execute this kernel      
          concurrently with other workloads, consider reducing the block size to have at least one block per            
          multiprocessor or increase the size of the grid to fully utilize the available hardware resources.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,21
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,79
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,89
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 16.1 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.89 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          30,37
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          32,60
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          30,37
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          12,89
    Stall Dispatch Stall                                                              inst                           0,01
    Stall Drain                                                                       inst                           0,02
    Stall IMC Miss                                                                    inst                           6,60
    Stall LG Throttle                                                                 inst                              0
    Stall Long Scoreboard                                                             inst                           7,06
    Stall Math Pipe Throttle                                                          inst                           0,02
    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                              0
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                           0,00
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,02
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,58
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,09
    Selected                                                                          inst                              1
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           1,10
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,58
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    28,57
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        23,86
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 12.9 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 42.4% of the total average of 30.4 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.                                                                                  
    ----- --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    WRN   Instructions are executed in warps, which are groups of 32 threads. Optimal instruction throughput is         
          achieved if all 32 threads of a warp execute the same instruction. The chosen launch configuration, early     
          thread completion, and divergent flow control can significantly lower the number of active threads in a warp  
          per cycle. This kernel achieves an average of 28.6 threads being active per cycle. This is further reduced    
          to 23.9 threads per warp due to predication. The compiler may use predication to avoid an actual branch.      
          Instead, all instructions are scheduled, but a per-thread condition code or predicate controls which threads  
          execute the instructions. Try to avoid different execution paths within a warp when possible. In addition,    
          ensure your kernel makes use of Independent Thread Scheduling, which allows a warp to reconverge after a      
          data-dependent conditional block by explicitly calling __syncwarp().

          multiprocessors. This can underutilize some multiprocessors. If you do not intend to execute this kernel      
          concurrently with other workloads, consider reducing the block size to have at least one block per            
          multiprocessor or increase the size of the grid to fully utilize the available hardware resources.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,29
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,71
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,93
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 15.9 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.93 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          30,64

    Selected                                                                          inst                              1

    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,58
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    28,80
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        24,02
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 12.2 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 39.7% of the total average of 30.6 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,29
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,71
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,88
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 15.9 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.88 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          29,96

    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,58
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    28,83
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        24,03
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 12.1 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 40.3% of the total average of 30.0 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,17
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,83
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           2,04
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 16.2 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          2.04 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          33,09
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          35,55
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          33,09
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          11,87

    Stall Drain                                                                       inst                           0,02

    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                              0
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                           0,00
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,02
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,59
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,09
    Selected                                                                          inst                              1
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           1,10
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,58
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    28,99
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        24,19
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 11.9 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 35.9% of the total average of 33.1 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.

    Section: Scheduler Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Instructions Per Active Issue Slot                                          inst/cycle                              1
    One or More Eligible                                                                 %                           6,37
    Issued Warp Per Scheduler                                                                                        0,06
    No Eligible                                                                          %                          93,63
    Theoretical Warps Per Scheduler                                                   warp                              8
    smsp__warps_active.avg.peak_sustained                                             warp                              8
    Active Warps Per Scheduler                                                        warp                           1,93
    Eligible Warps Per Scheduler                                                      warp                           0,07
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   Every scheduler is capable of issuing one instruction per cycle, but for this kernel each scheduler only      
          issues an instruction every 15.7 cycles. This might leave hardware resources underutilized and may lead to    
          less optimal performance. Out of the maximum of 8 warps per scheduler, this kernel allocates an average of    
          1.93 active warps per scheduler, but only an average of 0.07 warps were eligible per cycle. Eligible warps    
          are the subset of active warps that are ready to issue their next instruction. Every cycle with no eligible   
          warp results in no instruction being issued and the issue slot remains unused. To increase the number of      
          eligible warps either increase the number of active warps or reduce the time the active warps are stalled.    

    Section: Warp State Statistics
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    Warp Cycles Per Issued Instruction                                               cycle                          30,35
    Warp Cycles Per Executed Instruction                                             cycle                          32,52
    Warp Cycles Per Issue Active                                                      warp                          30,35
    Stall Barrier                                                                     inst                          13,38

    Stall Drain                                                                       inst                           0,02

    Stall Membar                                                                      inst                              0
    Stall MIO Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Misc                                                                        inst                           0,02
    Stall No Instruction                                                              inst                           0,59
    Stall Not Selected                                                                inst                           0,09
    Selected                                                                          inst                              1
    Stall Short Scoreboard                                                            inst                           1,08
    Stall Sleeping                                                                    inst                              0
    Stall Tex Throttle                                                                inst                              0
    Stall Wait                                                                        inst                           2,57
    smsp__issue_active.avg.per_cycle_active                                                                          0,06
    Avg. Active Threads Per Warp                                                                                    29,07
    Avg. Not Predicated Off Threads Per Warp                                                                        24,25
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------- --------------- ------------------------------
    WRN   On average each warp of this kernel spends 13.4 cycles being stalled waiting for sibling warps at a CTA       
          barrier. This represents about 44.1% of the total average of 30.4 cycles between issuing two instructions. A  
          high number of warps waiting at a barrier is commonly caused by diverging code paths before a barrier that    
          causes some warps to wait a long time until other warps reach the synchronization point. Whenever possible    
          try to divide up the work into blocks of uniform workloads. Use the Source View's sampling columns to         
          identify which barrier instruction causes the most stalls and optimize the code executed before that          
          synchronization point first.
